<DOC><DOCNO> AP900316-0094 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-16-90 1403EST</FILEID><FIRST>d a AM-BRF--WeaponsPlea     03-16 0152</FIRST><SECOND>AM-BRF--Weapons Plea,0154</SECOND><HEAD>Colombian Officer Pleads Guilty to Weapons Export</HEAD><DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A Colombian military officer pleaded guilty Fridayin federal court to charges that he attempted to export of weaponswithout a license.   First Lt. Ricardo Petersson Bernal, 26, was arrested Sept. 28when U.S. Customs Service agents found two semiautomatic rifles, a9mm semiautomatic pistol, a 12-gauge shotgun, 1,000 rounds ofammunition and a smoke grenade in his luggage checked for anAvianca flight to Bogota, Colombia.   Petersson said at an earlier hearing that he was taking theweapons to Colombia for people who wanted them for their ownprotection. A month before his arrest, the Colombian governmentstarted a nationwide attack on drug cartels, triggering widespreadbombings, kidnappings and other violence by traffickers.   Sentencing was not immediately scheduled. Petersson's attorney,Milton Hirsch, said that under sentencing guidelines his clientprobably would not get more than 10 months.</TEXT></DOC>